<div id="c4">
<p>I wonder if we&#8217;re using &#8216;identity&#8217; to mean different things. Let‚Äôs make a distinction (I‚Äôm a philosopher, I make distinctions compulsively): <em>identity(1)</em> is a way in which people are labelled and pigeonholed ‚Äì soccer mom, goth, juvenile delinquent; <em>identity(2)</em> is a deep unchosen fact about oneself ‚Äì I‚Äôd say that sexuality is one such, but even if not, there <em>are</em> such (I like humors as rough guides here: some people just are melancholic). You&#8217;re right that &#8216;having-sex-with-white-people&#8217; isn&#8217;t currently an identity(1) for me or you, although it could become one, and maybe even is one: one name for it would be &#8216;race traitor&#8217;. I&#8217;m inclined to think it isn&#8217;t even a possible identity(2) for creatures like us, given how fascinating, including sexually fascinating, humans seem to find difference. Identities(1) and (2) can fail to match: I can be misperceived by others, and damaged by that misperception. And in general ‚Äì I think ‚Äì it‚Äôs better for us to have identities(1) and (2) which do match ‚Äì to be seen as we are. That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs valuable that there is a recognised, non-hateful identity(1) ‚Äògay‚Äô to match some people‚Äôs gay identity(2). That doesn‚Äôt stop there being people for whom sexuality isn‚Äôt a part of identity(2) ‚Äì who enjoy having sex with people of both sexes, but don‚Äôt feel that anything deep in themselves is engaged when they do. I think they‚Äôre unusual people, to be honest; I know I‚Äôm not one of them.</p>

